{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"460d388d-b613-43e3-94c0-c7216a328910","content":"The standard approach is to **abstract the file system behind an interface** and inject it:\n\n1. **Define an interface** like `IFileSystem` with methods matching what you use (`WriteAllText`, `ReadAllText`, `DirectoryExists`).\n2. **Create a real implementation** that delegates to `System.IO.File` / `Directory`.\n3. **Inject `IFileSystem`** into your classes via constructor injection.\n4. **In tests**, pass a mock/fake implementation.\n\nAlternatively, use the built-in `System.IO.Abstractions` NuGet package — it provides `IFileSystem` out of the box with a `MockFileSystem` for testing, saving you from writing your own.\n\n```csharp\n// With System.IO.Abstractions:\npublic class MyService\n{\n    private readonly IFileSystem _fs;\n    public MyService(IFileSystem fs) => _fs = fs;\n\n    public void Save(string path, string data)\n        => _fs.File.WriteAllText(path, data);\n}\n\n// In tests:\nvar fs = new MockFileSystem();\nvar svc = new MyService(fs);\nsvc.Save(\"/tmp/test.txt\", \"hello\");\nAssert.Equal(\"hello\", fs.File.ReadAllText(\"/tmp/test.txt\"));\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"7fe3172e-9635-471b-8c69-ea036c8687f8","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about making file system operations testable in .NET code. This is a design/architecture question about testability, not a code change request. Let me provide a concise answer.","outputTokens":364,"requestId":"CFD4:1CA5E9:5FF3703:6BACAE1:69EC1C83"},"id":"12fbe165-716f-4d4c-8229-207396c262e6","timestamp":"2026-04-25T01:44:44.478Z","parentId":"d5f0e925-295f-473e-8986-87807fddc51a"}
